translated into Modern Chinese 
 
 
 
 
 
Notice how Classical Chinese often makes use of different roots from the modern 
language (yǐn, for modern hē ‘drink,’ shí for modern chī ‘eat,’ the former of which  
survive in the common words for ‘drink’ and ‘eat’ in Cantonese), but they also tend more 
to single-syllable words (rì – tàiyang; zuò – gōngzuò; xī – xiūxi; hé - shénme). Almost all 
the words in the classical original above appear in the modern standard language, but 
often in compounds (yǐn > yǐnliào ‘beverages’, xī > xiūxi ‘to rest’) or with different 
meanings (rì ‘day’ rather than ‘sun’). 
 
 
 
 
 

 

